<TITLE> 'Facebook culprit' in police remand </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, May 30 (bdnews24.com)  A magistrate on Sunday gave the police three days to question Mahbub Alam Rodin alias Brigadier Mahdi for allegedly committing "cyber crime". Rodin is claimed to have posted caricatures of prime minister Sheikh Hasina and main opposition BNP chairperson Khaleda Zia, along with obnoxious comments, on the social networking site Facebook. The government blocked the site on Saturday following a request from the Rapid Action Battalion. The social networking site has since been closed. The elite force RAB arrested Rodin from an apartment building at Wari's Rankin Street early on Saturday. Magistrate Nazrul Islam of Dhaka's Chief Metropolitan Magistrate's Court on Sunday approved the three-day remand following a seven-day remand application made by sub-inspector Ashikur Rahman of Sutrapur Police Station. Traffic inspector Mohammad Mahbubul Haque had filed cases under the Information and Technology Act and Passport Act on Sunday. The court's general recording officer Shakhawat Hossain said Rodin is experienced in information technology and is alleged to be directly involved with various cyber crimes. Rodin also had more than one passport which he had forged, he said 
